#!perl

our $DATE = '2019-04-23'; # DATE
our $VERSION = '0.033'; # VERSION

use 5.010001;
use strict;
use warnings;

use App::INIUtils;
use App::INIUtils::Common;
use Perinci::CmdLine::Any;

our %SPEC;
$SPEC{map_ini} = {
    v => 1.1,
    summary => 'Modify INI section/key/value using Perl code',
    args => {
        %App::INIUtils::args_common,
        %App::INIUtils::Common::args_map,
    },
    result_naked => 1,
    'cmdline.skip_format' => 1,
};
sub map_ini {
    my %args = @_;

    my $reader = App::INIUtils::_get_ciir_reader(\%args);

    my $hoh = $reader->read_string($args{ini});
    $hoh = App::INIUtils::Common::map_hoh(hoh => $hoh, %args);
    App::INIUtils::Common::hoh_as_ini($hoh);
}

my $cli = Perinci::CmdLine::Any->new(
    url => '/main/map_ini',
    read_config => 0,
    read_env => 0,
);

$cli->run;

# ABSTRACT: Modify INI section/key/value using Perl code
# PODNAME: map-ini

__END__

=pod

=encoding UTF-8

=head1 NAME

map-ini - Modify INI section/key/value using Perl code

=head1 VERSION

This document describes version 0.033 of map-ini (from Perl distribution App-INIUtils), released on 2019-04-23.

=head1 SYNOPSIS

Examples:

 # make section names uppercase
 % map-ini --section '$_ = uc' /path/to/file.ini

 # prepend key name with section name
 % map-ini --key '$_ = "$SECTION.$_"' /path/to/file.ini

 # prepend value with section and key name
 % map-ini --value '$_ = "$SECTION.$KEY.$_"' /path/to/file.ini

=head1 OPTIONS

C<*> marks required options.

=head2 Main options

=over

=item B<--key>=I<s>

=item B<--section>=I<s>

=item B<--value>=I<s>

=back

=head2 Parser options

=over

=item B<--default-section>=I<s>

Default value:

 "GLOBAL"

=item B<--disallow-duplicate-key>

=back

=head2 Other options

=over

=item B<--help>, B<-h>, B<-?>

Display help message and exit.

=item B<--ini>=I<s>*

INI file.

=item B<--version>, B<-v>

Display program's version and exit.

=back

=head1 COMPLETION

This script has shell tab completion capability with support for several
shells.

=head2 bash

To activate bash completion for this script, put:

 complete -C map-ini map-ini

in your bash startup (e.g. F<~/.bashrc>). Your next shell session will then
recognize tab completion for the command. Or, you can also directly execute the
line above in your shell to activate immediately.

It is recommended, however, that you install modules using L<cpanm-shcompgen>
which can activate shell completion for scripts immediately.

=head2 tcsh

To activate tcsh completion for this script, put:

 complete map-ini 'p/*/`map-ini`/'

in your tcsh startup (e.g. F<~/.tcshrc>). Your next shell session will then
recognize tab completion for the command. Or, you can also directly execute the
line above in your shell to activate immediately.

It is also recommended to install L<shcompgen> (see above).

=head2 other shells

For fish and zsh, install L<shcompgen> as described above.

